Notes: Web dev projects have a pretty predictable meeting ‚Äúarc.‚Äù Here‚Äôs the usual flow from day zero to launch (and after), with what each meeting is actually for in real life‚Äînot just the calendar label.

_____________Beginning of Pre-Code Meetings_____________________

1. Discovery / Intro Call

When: Before anything is scoped or quoted
Who: Client, PM, sometimes tech lead
Purpose:

Understand the problem (not the solution yet)

Business goals, users, constraints

Budget range, timeline expectations

Red flags on both sides üòÖ

Typical outputs:

High-level requirements

Go / no-go decision

Next steps (proposal or workshop)

_________________________________________________________
2. Requirements / Discovery Workshop

When: Early, after intro call
Who: Client stakeholders, PM, UX, tech lead
Purpose:

Dig into features, workflows, edge cases

Define user personas & journeys

Clarify integrations, data, permissions

Typical outputs:

Functional requirements

Feature list or backlog

Early assumptions and risks

_______________________________________________________________

3. Technical Scoping / Architecture Meeting

When: After requirements start to solidify
Who: Developers, tech lead, sometimes PM
Purpose:

Choose stack, frameworks, hosting

Discuss performance, security, scalability

Identify technical risks & tradeoffs

Typical outputs:

Architecture diagram

Tech stack decisions

Complexity estimates


_______________________________________________________________
4. Estimation & Planning Meeting

When: Before contracts or sprint planning
Who: Dev team, PM
Purpose:

Break features into tasks

Estimate time/effort

Decide delivery approach (phases, MVP)

Typical outputs:

Timeline

Cost estimate

Milestones

_______________________________________________________________

5. Kickoff Meeting

When: Official project start
Who: Everyone
Purpose:

Align on goals, scope, timeline

Clarify roles & communication rules

Set expectations (what won‚Äôt be done too)

Typical outputs:

Shared understanding

Project calendar

Communication channels (Slack, Jira, etc.)

_________________________________________________________________________

6. Design Review Meetings

When: Early‚Äìmid project
Who: Client, designers, dev lead
Purpose:

Review wireframes / UI designs

Catch usability issues before code

Ensure designs are feasible to build

Typical outputs:

Approved designs

Change requests

Design handoff to devs
____________________________________________________

7. Sprint Planning

When: Every sprint (Agile projects)
Who: Dev team, PM
Purpose:

Decide what gets built next

Assign tasks

Clarify acceptance criteria

Typical outputs:

Sprint backlog

Clear dev priorities

______________________End of pre code meetings______________________________

$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$$
8. Daily Standups

When: Daily or near-daily
Who: Dev team
Purpose:

What I did yesterday

What I‚Äôm doing today

What‚Äôs blocking me

Typical outputs:

Fast issue detection

Minimal paperwork (ideally)



9. Stakeholder Check-Ins / Status Updates

When: Weekly or bi-weekly
Who: Client, PM, lead dev
Purpose:

Show progress

Confirm priorities haven‚Äôt changed

Manage expectations

Typical outputs:

Feedback

Scope adjustments

Approval to continue

10. Technical Review / Code Review Meetings

When: Mid-project or as needed
Who: Devs
Purpose:

Review architecture decisions

Address tech debt

Align on coding standards

Typical outputs:

Refactoring decisions

Agreed best practices

11. QA / Testing Review

When: Feature-complete or near end
Who: QA, devs, PM
Purpose:

Review bugs and edge cases

Decide what‚Äôs a must-fix vs nice-to-have

Validate against requirements

Typical outputs:

Bug list

Release criteria

12. UAT (User Acceptance Testing) Review

When: Right before launch
Who: Client, PM, dev lead
Purpose:

Client validates the product

Catch last-minute issues

Final approval to launch

Typical outputs:

Sign-off

Final fixes

13. Launch / Go-Live Meeting

When: Deployment day
Who: Devs, PM, sometimes client
Purpose:

Coordinate deployment steps

Rollback plan

Monitor for issues

Typical outputs:

Live product üéâ

Post-launch checklist

14. Post-Launch Retrospective

When: After launch
Who: Team (sometimes client)
Purpose:

What went well

What didn‚Äôt

What to improve next time

Typical outputs:

Process improvements

Lessons learned

15. Maintenance / Roadmap Planning

When: After launch, ongoing
Who: Client, PM, dev lead
Purpose:

Plan enhancements

Handle bugs & support

Decide next phase

Typical outputs:

Product roadmap

Support plan
